      dek: `Editing is the final rewrite of your film — the stage where story, performance, and pace are actually decided, not just assembled. It's the most powerful and least understood craft in filmmaking, and once you see the edit as writing rather than trimming, everything about how you cut changes.`,
      body: `<p>Ask most beginners what editing is and they'll say something about trimming clips and adding transitions. That's not editing — that's the mechanics. <strong>Editing is the final rewrite of your film</strong>, and it's the single most important creative stage after the shoot, because it's where you actually decide what the story is, how it's told, which performances land, where the tension sits, and how fast or slow the whole thing breathes. A script is a plan and a shoot is raw material, but the film itself — the thing the audience experiences — is built in the edit. You can rescue a struggling scene, cut a subplot that isn't working, change the entire meaning of a moment by holding on a different face, and find a rhythm that turns flat footage into something alive. That's writing, not trimming. Once you understand that the edit is where the movie is genuinely made, you stop thinking like someone tidying up clips and start thinking like the last writer on the film — which is exactly what an editor is.</p>

<h2>Why the edit is where the film is made</h2>

<p>What editing actually controls:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Story and structure.</b> The order of scenes, what you keep, what you cut, where you start and end — you can restructure the entire film in the edit, and often you have to.</li>
  <li><b>Performance.</b> You choose which take, which line reading, which glance. You can build a great performance from pieces, or protect a weak one by cutting away at the right moment.</li>
  <li><b>Pace and rhythm.</b> How long a shot holds, when you cut, how fast a scene moves — pacing is created entirely in the edit, and it's the difference between gripping and boring.</li>
  <li><b>Emotion and meaning.</b> A cut to a reaction, a held silence, a hard cut on a word — editing decisions change how the audience <em>feels</em>, and even what a scene means.</li>
  <li><b>Clarity.</b> The edit is where you make sure the audience always knows where they are, who's who, and what just happened. Confusion is usually an editing problem.</li>
  <li><b>Time itself.</b> You compress hours into minutes, cross-cut two places at once, jump years in a single cut. Editing is control over the audience's experience of time.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Think like the last writer on the film</h2>

<p>The mindset shift that turns a clip-trimmer into an editor is this: <strong>you are the final rewrite</strong>. Everyone before you — the writer, the director, the crew, the actors — handed you material, and now it's your job to write the actual film out of it. That reframes every decision you'll make in this course. When a scene isn't working, you don't just tighten it; you ask what the film needs and whether that scene even belongs, the same way a writer interrogates a draft. When you pick a take, you're not choosing the "best" one in isolation, you're choosing the one that serves the story you're building. When you set the pace, you're writing the tempo of the audience's heartbeat. This is why editing is so powerful and so often underestimated: the same footage can become a completely different film in two different editors' hands, because the edit isn't assembly, it's authorship. It's also why editing is a real, learnable discipline with its own craft and its own workflow — which is what the rest of this course is about. We'll go step by step: how to set up a project so you can actually work (Chapter 2), how to choose your software (Chapter 3), the grammar of the cut itself (Chapter 4), then the real progression every film goes through — assembly, rough cut, fine cut, picture lock — plus pacing, dialogue, sound, and delivery. But it all rests on this foundation: the edit is not where you clean up the movie. It's where you write it. Treat it with the seriousness that deserves, and you'll cut films that work. Treat it as trimming, and you'll only ever tidy up footage that doesn't.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Editing isn't trimming clips — it's the final rewrite of your film. The same footage becomes a different movie in different hands, because the edit isn't assembly, it's authorship.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The first time I truly understood editing, I was staring at a scene that just wasn't working — flat, slow, dead. I'd shot it fine. But in the edit I cut the first half entirely, started later, held one reaction a beat too long on purpose, and suddenly it had tension it never had on set. Nothing new was shot. I just rewrote it in the timeline. That's when it clicked: editing isn't fixing the footage, it's writing the film with the footage. Ever since, I sit down to edit the way a writer sits down to a draft — asking what the story needs, not what's easiest to trim.</p>
</div>`,
