      dek: `Before you make a single cut, you set up the project — and this unglamorous step decides whether your edit is fast and calm or slow and chaotic. Media management, a clean folder structure, backups, and proxies aren't busywork; they're the foundation that lets you actually create instead of hunting for lost files.`,
      body: `<p>Nobody dreams of becoming an editor so they can name folders. But here's the truth every professional learns, usually the hard way: <strong>how you set up your project determines how well you can edit in it</strong>. An organized edit is a fast edit and a calm edit — you find the shot you want in seconds, your project doesn't crash, your media never goes offline, and your attention stays on the creative work. A disorganized edit is slow torture — you waste hours hunting for clips, your timeline links break, a drive dies and takes your work with it, and the mechanical friction quietly kills your creativity. Setup is boring for about twenty minutes and then it pays you back every single day of the cut. So before you make a single edit, you get your media managed, your folders structured, your backups running, and your footage organized — because the goal is to build a project where the technology disappears and all that's left is you and the story.</p>

<h2>Setting up a project that works</h2>

<p>The foundation to lay before you cut:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>One clean folder structure.</b> Create a single project folder with clear subfolders — footage, audio, music, graphics, exports, project files. Everything lives in one place, named consistently. This one habit prevents most edit disasters.</li>
  <li><b>Back up everything, twice.</b> Your footage should exist on at least two drives, ideally three with one offsite or in the cloud. Drives fail. The 3-2-1 rule (three copies, two media types, one offsite) is not paranoia — it's insurance.</li>
  <li><b>Organize and label your media.</b> Import into bins by scene, day, or type. Rename or tag clips so you can find them. An hour organizing now saves ten hours of hunting later.</li>
  <li><b>Use proxies for heavy footage.</b> If your camera files are large (4K, RAW), generate smaller proxy files to edit smoothly, then relink to the originals for final export. Proxies keep the edit responsive on any machine.</li>
  <li><b>Match your sequence to your footage.</b> Set your timeline's resolution and frame rate to match how you shot. Getting this right at the start avoids weird conform and playback problems later.</li>
  <li><b>Save, autosave, and version.</b> Turn on autosave, and save incremental versions (v01, v02…) so you can always go back. A corrupted project with no backup is a nightmare you only have once.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Boring setup buys creative freedom</h2>

<p>The principle underneath all of this is simple: <strong>a well-organized project removes friction, and removing friction is what frees you to create</strong>. Every second you spend searching for a clip, waiting for stuttering playback to catch up, or re-linking offline media is a second stolen from the actual editing — and worse, it's a second that breaks your creative flow, because the moment you drop out of the story to solve a file-management problem, you have to climb all the way back into it. Great editors protect their focus ruthlessly, and the way you protect it is by doing the unglamorous setup work up front so nothing interrupts you later. This is why the pros are almost fanatical about organization: it isn't fussiness, it's the thing that lets them stay in the creative zone for hours at a stretch. And it's directly connected to the rest of this course, because everything ahead — the assembly, the rough cut, the fine cut, pacing, dialogue, the endless small decisions — all of it goes faster and feels better when your project is clean and your media is safe. It also connects backward, to the shoot: if your footage was well-labeled and your sound was well-organized on set, your edit setup is half done already. So resist the urge to just dump everything on the desktop and start cutting. Spend the twenty minutes. Build the folders, run the backups, generate the proxies, organize the bins, set the sequence. Make a project where the technology gets out of your way. Then, with the foundation solid and nothing between you and the footage, you're ready to actually start editing — beginning with the tool you'll do it in, which is next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">An organized edit is a fast, calm edit. Setup is boring for twenty minutes and then it pays you back every day of the cut — because removing friction is what frees you to create.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I learned media management the way most people do: by losing work. Early on I had everything scattered across a desktop, no real backup, and one morning the drive just didn't mount. Weeks of edit, gone. Now I'm almost boring about it — one project folder, clear bins, proxies for anything heavy, and the 3-2-1 backup running before I make a single cut. It costs me twenty minutes at the start and it has never once cost me a day since. The setup isn't the fun part. But it's the reason the fun part never gets interrupted.</p>
</div>`,
