      dek: `Premiere Pro, DaVinci Resolve, Final Cut Pro — beginners agonize over which editing software to pick, and it matters far less than they think. They all cut a film beautifully. Pick one, learn it deeply, and put your energy where it belongs: into editing, not into the tool.`,
      body: `<p>The single most over-agonized decision in editing is which software to use, and here's the liberating truth: <strong>the software barely matters</strong>. Premiere Pro, DaVinci Resolve, and Final Cut Pro are all professional, capable tools that will cut your film beautifully — the differences between them are real but small, and none of them is the reason a film succeeds or fails. Beginners burn weeks reading comparison threads and second-guessing their choice, as if the right program will make them a good editor. It won't. The craft of editing — the story sense, the timing, the taste — lives entirely in you and transfers between every one of these tools; the software is just where you do the work. So the right move is almost anticlimactic: pick one, ideally based on simple practical factors, learn it deeply enough that it disappears, and then forget about it and go edit. The editors you admire could cut a great film in any of these programs, because their skill was never in the software.</p>

<h2>The main tools and how to pick</h2>

<p>What actually separates them, and how to choose:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>DaVinci Resolve.</b> Has a genuinely powerful free version, runs on Mac and Windows, and includes world-class color grading built in. Hard to beat for a filmmaker on a budget, and increasingly a full editing home, not just a color tool.</li>
  <li><b>Adobe Premiere Pro.</b> The cross-platform industry workhorse, subscription-based, deeply integrated with After Effects and the Adobe ecosystem. Ubiquitous, well-documented, and a safe skill to have professionally.</li>
  <li><b>Final Cut Pro.</b> Mac-only, one-time purchase, famously fast and efficient with a magnetic timeline some editors love and others don't. Excellent performance on Apple hardware.</li>
  <li><b>Pick on practical factors.</b> Your budget, your computer (Mac vs Windows), what your collaborators use, and what tutorials you'll learn from matter more than any feature checklist.</li>
  <li><b>The fundamentals are the same.</b> Timelines, tracks, in and out points, cuts, trims, transitions — every editor works the same way. Learn the concepts once and they carry across all three.</li>
  <li><b>Commit and go deep.</b> Fluency in one tool beats dabbling in three. Learn your chosen software's shortcuts until your hands move without thinking — that speed is real editing power.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Pick one, learn it deeply, then forget it</h2>

<p>The mindset that serves you here is to treat software choice as a <strong>quick practical decision, not an identity or a strategy</strong>. Look at your situation — what you can afford, what machine you own, what the people around you use, what you can find good tutorials for — make a reasonable call in an afternoon, and then commit fully. The commitment is the important part, because the real return comes from depth: an editor fluent in one program, who knows the shortcuts cold and never has to think about the interface, is dramatically faster and freer than someone who half-knows three. When the tool disappears — when trimming, rippling, and slipping shots is as automatic as typing — your whole attention stays on the story, which is exactly where it should be. And that points to the deeper truth this chapter is really about: the software is not the craft. Everything else in this course — the language of the cut, the assembly, the rough and fine cut, pacing, dialogue, the taste to know what works — none of it belongs to Premiere or Resolve or Final Cut. It belongs to you, and it transfers to any tool you'll ever touch. Great editors have cut on film with razor blades, on tape, and on every one of these programs, and they were great in all of them, because the skill was never in the machine. So stop agonizing. Pick the one that fits your budget and your computer, watch enough tutorials to get fluent, learn the shortcuts until your hands know them, and then put the comparison threads away for good. Your energy is far better spent learning to edit than learning to shop — and learning to edit starts with the grammar of the cut itself, which is next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The software barely matters — Premiere, Resolve, and Final Cut all cut a film beautifully. Pick one, learn it until it disappears, and put your energy into editing, not into the tool.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I've cut professionally in all three of these programs, and I'll tell you a secret: my edits weren't better or worse depending on which one I opened. When a project needed color, I leaned on Resolve. When it lived in the Adobe world, Premiere. On a fast Mac job, Final Cut. The films came out the same, because the part that mattered — the story sense, the timing — came with me. My advice to every beginner who asks "which should I learn?" is the same: whichever one you can afford and run, and then stop asking. Go deep, get fast, and let the tool vanish.</p>
</div>`,
