      desc: "The first pass — getting the whole film onto the timeline, ugly and long.",
      time: "8 min",
      moduleKey: "core",
      kicker: "Core Craft",
      seoTitle: "The Assembly Edit: Getting the Whole Film on the Timeline | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "The film assembly edit — how to build your first pass, string out the whole movie long and rough, and resist the urge to polish before you have the shape. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 5 of The Editing Workflow.",
      dek: `The first real pass is the assembly — the whole film strung together, long and ugly and complete. Its only job is to exist, not to be good. Get the entire movie onto the timeline before you polish a single frame, and you'll have something you can actually shape.`,
      body: `<p>Now you actually start cutting — and the first pass has a specific name and a specific job. It's called the <strong>assembly</strong>, and its only purpose is to get the entire film onto the timeline, in order, from beginning to end. It will be long. It will be clunky. Scenes will run way past where they should, the pacing will be a mess, and it won't be good — and that's exactly right, because the assembly isn't supposed to be good. It's supposed to <em>exist</em>. The single biggest mistake beginners make is trying to perfect the first scene before they've built the rest of the film: they polish scene one to a shine, then scene two, and run out of energy long before they have a whole movie — and worse, they've fussed over scenes that the shape of the film might demand they cut entirely. The assembly frees you from that trap. You lay the whole thing down first, ugly and complete, so that for the first time you can see your actual film and start making decisions about the whole instead of obsessing over the parts.</p>

<h2>How to build the assembly</h2>

<p>The way to get the whole film down:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Work scene by scene, in order.</b> Take each scene, pick the takes and coverage that work, and cut it together roughly. Move to the next. Don't loop back to polish — keep moving forward.</li>
  <li><b>Include everything.</b> Put in every scene, and lean long — keep more than you think you need. It's far easier to cut later than to rediscover something you dropped. The assembly is generous by design.</li>
  <li><b>Follow your plan, then trust the footage.</b> Start from the script and your paper edit, but stay open — sometimes a scene plays better a different way than planned. Note it and move on.</li>
  <li><b>Don't polish. Don't perfect.</b> No fine trims, no transitions, no color, no sound work. Rough cuts joined end to end. Perfection now is wasted effort on scenes that may change or vanish.</li>
  <li><b>Get to "The End."</b> Your goal is a complete film from first frame to last, however rough. Finishing the assembly is a milestone — for the first time, the whole movie exists in one place.</li>
  <li><b>Then step back and watch it.</b> Screen the whole assembly start to finish. Now — and only now — you can see what your film actually is, and start shaping it.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Get it all down before you make it good</h2>

<p>The principle that makes the assembly work is <strong>separating building from polishing</strong> — and doing them in that order, never mixed. When you try to perfect as you go, you make two mistakes at once: you burn your best energy on the earliest scenes while the ending gets whatever's left, and you polish material before you know whether it even belongs, because you can't know what a scene needs to be until you can see it in the context of the whole film. The assembly solves both by insisting you get everything down first, rough and complete, and only then begin to shape. This is the same wisdom writers live by — a first draft exists to be finished, not to be good, and you can't edit a blank page. The assembly is your first draft on the timeline: its ugliness is not failure, it's the necessary raw form of a film you can finally see and work on. And seeing the whole thing changes everything, because editing decisions are decisions about the whole — how long this scene should run depends on what comes before and after it, whether a subplot earns its place depends on the shape of the entire story, and where the film drags or races only reveals itself when you watch it end to end. You simply cannot make those calls from a single polished scene. So resist with everything you've got the urge to perfect scene one. Build the whole film first, generously and roughly, get all the way to "The End," and then sit down and watch what you actually have. That complete, imperfect assembly is the thing the rest of the edit will shape — and shaping it, turning that rough draft into a rough cut and then a fine cut, is exactly where we go next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The assembly isn't supposed to be good — it's supposed to exist. Get the whole film onto the timeline, long and ugly and complete, before you polish a single frame. You can't shape a movie you can't see.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>On my first feature I spent two weeks making the opening scene perfect — gorgeous, tight, flawless. Then I built the rest of the film, watched it back, and realized the opening didn't belong there at all; the movie actually started better ten minutes in. Two weeks, gone, on a scene I cut. That taught me the assembly discipline for life: get the whole thing down first, rough as hell, all the way to the end, and don't fall in love with any scene until you can see the entire film. Build first. Polish later. Never the other way around.</p>
</div>`,
