      seoDesc: "From rough cut to fine cut — how a film is shaped through successive drafts, killing your darlings, screening for feedback, and refining toward picture lock. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 6 of The Editing Workflow.",
      dek: `A film is shaped the way a sculpture is carved — not in one pass, but through drafts. From the rough cut to the fine cut, you refine in layers, cutting the fat, killing your darlings, and screening for feedback until the film finds its true, tight form.`,
      body: `<p>Once your assembly exists, the real editing begins — and it happens the way all good work happens, <strong>through drafts</strong>. You don't go from rough assembly to finished film in one heroic pass; you refine in layers, each one tighter and truer than the last. The assembly becomes the rough cut, where you make the big structural decisions and get the film into a real shape. The rough cut becomes the fine cut, where you polish scene by scene, frame by frame, until every moment earns its place. It's carving: you start with the whole rough block and keep removing everything that isn't the film. Along the way you'll do the hardest and most important thing an editor does — <em>kill your darlings</em>, cutting beautiful moments that don't serve the whole — and you'll screen the film for trusted eyes to find out where it actually drags, because you're far too close to see it clearly on your own. Draft by draft, the film gets shorter, sharper, and more itself.</p>

<h2>Refining through the drafts</h2>

<p>The progression from rough to fine:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Rough cut: fix the structure.</b> Watch the assembly and make the big calls — reorder scenes, cut whole sequences that don't work, tighten each scene's length. You're solving the film's shape, not its details.</li>
  <li><b>Cut the fat, everywhere.</b> Almost every scene is too long. Get in later, get out earlier, trim the dead air. Tightening is the most reliable way to make almost any film better.</li>
  <li><b>Kill your darlings.</b> The gorgeous shot, the funny line, the scene you fought to get — if it doesn't serve the whole film, it has to go. This is the hardest discipline in editing and the most important.</li>
  <li><b>Fine cut: polish the details.</b> Now work scene by scene on exact cut points, timing, performance beats, rhythm. Frame-accurate trims. This is where the film goes from working to sharp.</li>
  <li><b>Screen for feedback.</b> Show cuts to trusted people and watch <em>with</em> them — you feel every slow spot through their eyes. Note where they drift, get confused, or check out, then re-cut.</li>
  <li><b>Iterate without ego.</b> Take real feedback, make another draft, screen again. Each pass gets tighter. Knowing when it's done — when more cutting stops helping — is part of the craft.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Carve the film out of the block</h2>

<p>The mental model that makes this stage click is <strong>sculpture, not construction</strong>. You're not adding to build the film up; you're removing to reveal the film that's hiding inside your footage, and every draft strips away more of what isn't it. That reframes the whole process as a series of subtractions, each one bringing the true shape closer — and it explains why "cut the fat" and "kill your darlings" are the two most repeated pieces of advice in all of editing. Cutting the fat works because length is the enemy of momentum: nearly every scene, every shot, every beat can start a little later and end a little earlier, and the accumulated tightening across a whole film is the difference between a story that grips and one that sags. Killing your darlings is harder because it hurts — you're cutting the moments you love most, the shot that took all day, the line that makes you laugh every time — but the test is never "do I love this," it's "does the film need this," and a self-indulgent moment that serves only itself weakens everything around it. And you cannot do either well alone, which is why screening matters so much: you know the film too intimately to feel its slow spots, but the second you sit beside someone watching it fresh, every draggy stretch becomes physically obvious to you, and their honest reactions are the most valuable editing notes you'll ever get. So you draft, and screen, and draft again — rough cut for structure, fine cut for polish, each pass shorter and sharper, killing darlings and cutting fat and taking feedback without ego — until you reach the point where more cutting stops helping and the film is simply itself. That point, when the film is as tight and true as it's going to get, is when you're ready to lock it — but before we get there, two things shape the fine cut more than almost anything else: pace and rhythm, which is next, and the way you handle dialogue. Carve patiently, remove everything that isn't the film, and the movie that was buried in your assembly will finally stand clear.</p>

<div class="pullquote">You don't finish a film in one pass — you carve it through drafts, removing everything that isn't the film. Cut the fat, kill your darlings, and screen for the slow spots you're too close to see.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The scene I was proudest of on one film — beautifully shot, perfectly performed — was the one I finally cut. Every test screening died in the same spot, and it was that scene: gorgeous, and completely unnecessary to the story. I resisted for three drafts. The day I finally pulled it, the whole film tightened and came alive. That's the lesson that never stops being true: the question is never whether you love a moment, it's whether the film needs it. And you'll only find out by watching it with fresh eyes in the room. Cut the fat. Kill the darlings. The film gets better every time you do.</p>
</div>`,
