      dek: `Pacing is the invisible engine of a film — the reason a scene grips or drags, races or breathes. It's created entirely in the edit, through shot length and cutting rhythm, and it's felt more than analyzed. Learn to feel it, and you can hold an audience in your hand.`,
      body: `<p>Ask an audience why they loved a film and they'll rarely say "the pacing" — but pacing is exactly why they stayed gripped or started checking their phone. <strong>Pacing and rhythm are the invisible engine of a film</strong>, and they live entirely in the edit. How long each shot holds, how fast you cut, when you speed up and when you let a moment breathe — these decisions create the film's heartbeat, and that heartbeat is what an audience actually experiences as tension, momentum, boredom, or dread. A scene that drags isn't badly written or badly acted, usually; it's badly paced, held too long, cut too slowly for what it's carrying. And pacing isn't just "fast good, slow bad" — great editing is about the <em>contrast</em>, the ebb and flow, the fast passages that make the slow ones land and the quiet moments that make the bursts hit. The tricky, wonderful thing about pacing is that it's felt more than thought. You learn it by watching, by cutting, by feeling when a scene wants to move and when it wants to hold — until timing becomes instinct.</p>

<h2>How pacing is built</h2>

<p>The levers that control your film's rhythm:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Shot length.</b> The single biggest pacing tool. Short shots accelerate and energize; long, held shots slow things down and create weight, tension, or calm. Every hold is a choice.</li>
  <li><b>Cutting speed.</b> Rapid cuts build energy and urgency — a chase, an argument, a montage. Slower cutting lets a scene breathe and an emotion register. Match the cut rate to what the scene needs.</li>
  <li><b>Contrast and dynamics.</b> Pacing works through change. A fast sequence hits harder after a slow one; a held silence lands because of the noise before it. Build in variation, not one relentless speed.</li>
  <li><b>The scene's internal rhythm.</b> Even within a scene, pace rises and falls — build toward a beat, cut faster into the peak, then release. Feel where a scene accelerates and where it should linger.</li>
  <li><b>Let moments breathe.</b> Not everything should be tight. A held reaction, a beat of silence, an extra second on a face — giving key moments room is as important as trimming the fat elsewhere.</li>
  <li><b>Cut to the feeling.</b> Ultimately you're not cutting to a formula, you're cutting to how the scene should <em>feel</em>. Trust the instinct that says "hold" or "go" — and build that instinct by watching how great films move.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Learn to feel the rhythm</h2>

<p>The truth about pacing is that it's a <strong>felt skill, not a formula</strong> — and that's exactly why it separates good editors from great ones. There's no rule that says a shot should be four seconds or a scene should cut every two; the right length is whatever makes the scene feel the way it needs to feel, and only your instinct, developed over time, can tell you that. This is where editing stops being technical and becomes almost musical, because pacing really is rhythm — the film has a tempo, scenes have a beat, and cutting well is a kind of playing in time. You develop the ear the same way musicians do: by immersion and repetition. Watch films actively and notice when you lean in and when you drift, then go back and see what the editor did with shot length and cut speed at exactly those moments. Cut your own scenes, watch them, feel where they sag or rush, and re-cut until they move right. Over hundreds of these small judgments, timing migrates from something you calculate to something you sense, and one day you'll trim a shot by six frames not because you measured it but because it simply felt long — and it was. Two principles will carry you a long way while that instinct develops. First, when in doubt, tighten: most beginner scenes are too slow, holding shots long after they've delivered, so the reliable move is to cut sooner than feels comfortable and let the scene push forward. Second, respect contrast: a film that's all one speed, however fast, becomes numbing, so vary your rhythm and let the fast and slow define each other. Pacing connects to everything else in this course — it's the fine cut's most powerful tool, it's what "cutting the fat" is really about, and it's central to dialogue, which we turn to next, where the rhythm of reactions and pauses is the whole game. Learn to feel the rhythm of your film, cut to how it should move rather than to any rule, and you'll hold your audience exactly where you want them — leaning in, breath held, never once thinking about the edit that's doing it to them.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Pacing is the invisible engine — it's why a scene grips or drags, and it's created entirely in the edit. You don't calculate it, you feel it: cut to how the scene should move, not to any rule.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Early on, a mentor watched my cut and said one thing: "It's all the same speed." He was right — every scene moved at the same steady clip, and it was numbing. He had me cut one sequence fast and hard, then let the scene right after it sit and breathe, and suddenly both scenes came alive because of the contrast between them. That's when pacing stopped being an abstraction for me. Now I feel a film like music — where it should race, where it should hold, where a single held second lands harder than any cut. You build that ear one scene at a time, and it never stops getting sharper.</p>
</div>`,
