      seoDesc: "How to edit dialogue scenes — building performance from takes, cutting to reactions, timing pauses, and why the listen matters more than the line. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 8 of The Editing Workflow.",
      dek: `Dialogue scenes are the backbone of most films, and cutting them well is a craft all its own. The secret isn't in the lines — it's in the reactions, the timing, and the listen. Great dialogue editing is about the person <em>not</em> speaking as much as the one who is.`,
      body: `<p>Most of the scenes you'll ever cut are two or more people talking, and there's a reason dialogue editing is where a lot of editors are quietly made or exposed. It looks simple — cut to whoever's speaking — and that's exactly the trap. A dialogue scene cut that way, ping-ponging to each speaker on cue, feels flat and mechanical, because <strong>a real conversation isn't about who's talking, it's about how people react to each other</strong>. The gold in a dialogue scene is usually on the face of the person <em>listening</em>: the flicker of doubt, the held breath, the look away, the moment a line lands. Great dialogue editing lives in reactions, in the timing of pauses, in when you cut away from a speaker to catch how their words are received. You're also building performance here — assembling the best line readings from different takes, protecting the emotional truth of the scene, and shaping the rhythm of the exchange so it feels like people really talking, not actors reciting. Cut to the listen, not just the line, and dialogue scenes come alive.</p>

<h2>How to cut a dialogue scene</h2>

<p>The techniques that make conversations feel real:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Cut to reactions, not just speakers.</b> The listener's face often carries the scene. Cut away from the talker to catch how a line lands — that reaction is frequently the most important shot in the exchange.</li>
  <li><b>Build the best performance from all takes.</b> You're not locked to one take. Assemble the strongest line readings and moments across every take and angle to build the best version of the performance.</li>
  <li><b>Time the pauses.</b> The silences between lines carry as much as the words — a beat before an answer, a held look. Tightening or lengthening a pause by a few frames changes the whole feel.</li>
  <li><b>Lean on L-cuts and J-cuts.</b> Overlap sound and picture so we hear a line while watching a reaction, or hear the next line before we cut to it. This weaves the conversation together naturally.</li>
  <li><b>Don't cut on every line.</b> Resist the ping-pong. Sometimes hold on one person through several lines, or stay on a listener. Let the scene breathe instead of mechanically following the speaker.</li>
  <li><b>Protect the emotional truth.</b> The "cleanest" take isn't always the truest. Choose the reading and rhythm that serve the scene's real feeling, even if it's a little messier.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Cut to the listen, not the line</h2>

<p>The principle that transforms dialogue editing is understanding that <strong>a conversation on screen is an exchange of reactions, not a relay of lines</strong> — and once you internalize that, you stop cutting to whoever's mouth is moving and start cutting to wherever the meaning is. Very often the meaning isn't on the speaker at all; it's on the listener, whose face is telling us what the words are doing to them, and knowing when to leave the talker to catch that reaction is the core skill of the whole craft. This is also where you quietly become a performance builder: because you have multiple takes and angles, you're not stuck with any single delivery, and you can construct a better, truer performance than exists in any one take by choosing the best reading of each line, the best reaction to each beat, the best rhythm for the exchange — protecting the scene's emotional honesty above technical cleanness. And timing is everything, because dialogue is musical: the pauses are notes too, and the difference between a scene that feels alive and one that feels stiff is often just a few frames added or removed from the silences between lines. All of this leans hard on tools from earlier in this course — the L-cuts and J-cuts from the language of the cut are your constant companions here, and the pacing instinct from the last chapter is exactly what tells you how long to hold a reaction or a pause. Resist the beginner reflex to cut on every single line as if you're obligated to show each speaker; the mechanical ping-pong is what makes amateur dialogue scenes feel dead. Instead, hold when holding serves the scene, cut away to reactions when the reaction is the story, time the pauses like a musician, and build the truest performance you can from everything you were given. Do that, and your dialogue scenes stop feeling like people taking turns reciting and start feeling like human beings actually talking, listening, and being changed by each other — which is the entire point. Next, we bring in the other half of every scene: sound and music.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A conversation on screen isn't a relay of lines — it's an exchange of reactions. The gold is usually on the face of the person listening. Cut to the listen, not just the line.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The scene that taught me dialogue editing had a big emotional confession in it, and my first cut just followed the speaker through the whole speech. Dead. Then I tried something: I stayed on the listener's face for most of it, catching every flinch and swallow as the words hit her — and only cut back to the speaker at the very end. Same footage, completely different scene. That's when I understood: the person not talking is often the one telling the story. Now I always ask, in every dialogue beat, "where's the reaction I need to see?" — because that's usually the shot that matters.</p>
</div>`,
