      dek: `A short film is where all of this comes together — and it's the most unforgiving format there is. With only minutes to work, every second must earn its place, so the whole workflow you've learned gets applied at its most ruthless. Editing a short is the fastest way to become a real editor.`,
      body: `<p>The short film is where everything in this course meets reality — and it's a brutal teacher, in the best way. A feature can carry a slow patch or a scene that only half-works; a short cannot. With only a handful of minutes, <strong>every second has to earn its place</strong>, and there's nowhere for flab to hide. That's exactly why editing a short film is the fastest, most concentrated way to learn the craft: the whole workflow you've built — organize, assemble, rough cut, fine cut, pace, cut dialogue, kill your darlings — gets applied at its most ruthless, and the feedback is immediate, because a single slack moment in a five-minute film is glaringly obvious. Shorts are also unforgiving of self-indulgence: the gorgeous long take, the extra beat you love, the scene that's "nice" but not necessary — in a short, all of it has to justify itself or go. Learn to edit a short tightly, and you've learned the discipline that makes every longer edit better. This chapter is the whole course applied to one complete, achievable film.</p>

<h2>Applying the workflow to a short</h2>

<p>How the whole process plays out on a short film:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Start from a clean setup.</b> Organized media, backups, proxies if needed — same foundation as any edit (Chapter 2). On a short you'll feel a messy project instantly.</li>
  <li><b>Assemble the whole thing first.</b> Build the complete short, rough and a little long, before polishing anything. Even at five minutes, get the full shape down before you refine (Chapter 5).</li>
  <li><b>Cut ruthlessly to the essential.</b> A short lives or dies on economy. Find the core of the story and cut everything that isn't it. Start scenes late, end them early, lose whole beats if they don't serve the whole.</li>
  <li><b>Nail the opening and the ending.</b> Shorts have seconds to hook and one shot to land. Spend real attention on your first moments and your final image — they carry disproportionate weight.</li>
  <li><b>Pace it tight, then find the breath.</b> Keep it moving, but still give the one or two key moments room to land. Even a tight short needs a little air where it counts (Chapter 7).</li>
  <li><b>Screen it and re-cut.</b> Short enough to watch fresh many times. Show it, feel every dead frame through an audience, and keep tightening until not one second is wasted.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Where the whole course comes together</h2>

<p>Editing a short film is the moment this entire course stops being a set of separate lessons and becomes <strong>one integrated skill</strong>. You'll use the setup discipline, the assembly-first habit, the draft-by-draft refining, the killing of darlings, the pacing instinct, the dialogue craft — all of it, on one complete film, in a format so compressed that any weakness in any of those areas shows up immediately. That's the gift of the short: the tight running time is a merciless but honest teacher, because you can't bury a mistake in length. If a scene drags, you feel it. If a moment is self-indulgent, it sticks out. If the opening doesn't hook or the ending doesn't land, there's no runway to recover. So the short forces you to internalize the single most important editing value there is — economy, the relentless commitment to making every second earn its place — and once you've truly learned that on a short, it never leaves you. It's also enormously practical: shorts are the format most emerging filmmakers actually finish and show, the calling card that gets into festivals and gets you seen, and the edit is often what separates a short that plays and a short that dies in the room. Give it the same seriousness a feature deserves, compressed. Get the whole thing down, then carve it to its essential core, protect the opening and the ending, keep it moving while letting the key beat breathe, and screen it over and over, cutting until nothing is wasted. Do that, and you won't just have a tight short film — you'll have proven to yourself that the whole workflow is now yours. The film is basically there. Two things remain before it's truly finished: the sound and music that fill it out, which is next, and then locking it and delivering it clean.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A short film has nowhere for flab to hide — every second has to earn its place. It's the most unforgiving format there is, which makes it the fastest way to become a real editor.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My sharpest editing lessons all came from shorts, because a short punishes every mistake instantly. On one five-minute film I had a beautiful ninety-second opening I adored — and it was killing the whole thing, delaying the story past where any audience would wait. Cutting it down to fifteen seconds hurt, but suddenly the short worked. That's the short-film discipline: there's no length to hide behind, so you learn economy the hard way and it stays with you forever. Every feature I've cut since is tighter because I learned to edit shorts where every single second had to fight for its life.</p>
</div>`,
