      desc: "Temp sound and music in the edit — and why audio is half your film.",
      time: "8 min",
      moduleKey: "apply",
      kicker: "Putting It to Work",
      seoTitle: "Sound & Music in the Edit: Temp Tracks & the Half You Can't See | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Sound and music in the edit — temp tracks, cutting to music, why audio is half your film, and how to work with sound in the picture edit before the handoff to post. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 10 of The Editing Workflow.",
      dek: `Sound is half your film — and it starts shaping the cut long before the final mix. Temp tracks, music, and audio choices in the picture edit make or break how a scene feels. Ignore sound until the end and you're editing with one sense missing.`,
      body: `<p>There's an old saying that <strong>sound is half the film</strong>, and it's not an exaggeration — audience emotion is driven by what they hear at least as much as by what they see, and yet beginners routinely treat sound as an afterthought, something to "fix later." That's a mistake, because sound starts shaping your picture edit whether you acknowledge it or not. The moment you drop a piece of temp music under a scene, the whole rhythm changes — cuts that felt fine now feel wrong, a scene that dragged suddenly flows, an emotional beat lands twice as hard. Sound and picture are partners, and the smart editor works with sound throughout the cut, not just at the end. That doesn't mean you're doing the final mix or the finished score in the edit — that specialized finishing work comes later, in the handoff to post. But you are absolutely making sound decisions the whole way through: laying in temp music to find the feel, keeping your dialogue clean and clear, blocking in effects and ambience where they matter. Edit with your ears as well as your eyes, and your cut gets better.</p>

<h2>Working with sound in the cut</h2>

<p>What to do with audio during the picture edit:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Use temp music to find the feel.</b> Drop in placeholder music to test a scene's tone and rhythm. It transforms how the cut plays and helps you find the pacing — just know it's temporary and must be replaced or licensed later.</li>
  <li><b>Cut picture and music together.</b> When a scene rides on music, edit the visuals to the beat and phrasing. Cutting to music is one of the most powerful tools you have for montage and emotion.</li>
  <li><b>Keep dialogue clean and clear.</b> Above all, the audience must understand every word. Choose takes for clean audio too, smooth over bumps, and never let a great-looking take with unusable sound win by default.</li>
  <li><b>Block in key sound effects and ambience.</b> You don't design the full soundscape, but roughing in the important sounds — a door, a crash, room tone — helps the cut feel real and shows what post needs to build.</li>
  <li><b>Mind your levels roughly.</b> Balance dialogue, music, and effects enough that the cut plays clearly for screenings. It won't be the final mix, but it shouldn't be a mess either.</li>
  <li><b>Edit with your ears.</b> Watch the cut with the sound up, and notice how audio is steering your reactions. If a scene isn't working, the fix is often in the sound, not the picture.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Half the film lives in the ears — and hands off to post</h2>

<p>The core idea to carry from this chapter is that <strong>sound is not a finishing touch, it's a creative partner in the edit from early on</strong> — and treating it that way makes you a dramatically better editor. When you cut with temp music and rough sound in place, you're feeling the film the way an audience will, with both senses engaged, and you catch things you'd never notice cutting in silence: a scene that plays flat visually might come alive under the right track, a pause that looks too long might feel perfect once there's ambience under it, an emotional beat might need one more second of music to land. That's why the pros build sound into the cut instead of bolting it on afterward. There's an important boundary here, though, and it's worth being clear about: working with sound in the edit is not the same as finishing the sound. The full craft — professional sound design, the final mix, dialogue cleanup and ADR, a bespoke score, music you've properly licensed — is a specialized stage that happens after picture lock, in the handoff to post, and it has its own courses and its own experts. What you do in the edit is the creative groundwork: you use temp music and rough sound to shape the film and prove out the feeling, and you deliver a locked cut whose sound intentions are clear, so the sound team and composer know exactly what you're going for. Two cautions matter. First, temp music is temporary — it's a fantastic tool for finding the feel, but you cannot ship it without rights, and you'll either license it or have a composer score to picture, so love the effect, not the specific track. Second, protect your dialogue above everything; clarity of the spoken word is non-negotiable, and it's an editing decision as much as a mix decision. Do all this — cut with your ears, use temp music to find the rhythm, keep dialogue pristine, block in the sounds that matter — and your picture edit will be tighter, truer, and ready to hand off. And handing off cleanly is exactly the next step: locking picture and passing the film to color, sound, and finishing.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Sound is half the film, and it shapes the cut long before the final mix. Drop in temp music and a scene transforms — so edit with your ears as much as your eyes, then hand a clear vision to post.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I had a scene that just wouldn't work — I recut it a dozen ways and it stayed lifeless. Out of frustration I dropped a piece of temp music under it, and instantly it played: same shots, same cuts, but now it had a pulse and an emotion it never had in silence. That taught me to bring sound in early, not at the end. I temp everything now — music, key effects, ambience — because I want to feel the film the way the audience will. Just remember the temp track is a placeholder; when the cut locks, it goes to a composer or gets licensed. Love what it does, not the song itself.</p>
</div>`,
