      dek: `At some point you stop cutting — you lock picture. It's a real, committed decision, and it unlocks the whole finishing stage: color, sound, and VFX teams can finally do their work on an edit that won't change under them. Knowing when and how to lock is the mark of a finisher.`,
      body: `<p>Editing could, in theory, go on forever — there's always one more trim, one more tweak, one more version. At some point you have to stop, and that moment has a name: <strong>picture lock</strong>. Locking picture means you declare the edit final — the shots, the order, the timing, the length are all set and will not change — and it is a real, deliberate, sometimes scary decision, because it means committing. But it's not just a milestone for you; it's the gate that unlocks the entire finishing stage. The color grade, the sound design and mix, the visual effects, the score — all of that specialized work is built precisely to the locked edit, frame for frame, and none of it can safely begin until the picture stops moving. If you keep re-cutting after handing off, you break everything downstream: the colorist's work no longer lines up, the sound mix drifts out of sync, the VFX shots are built to timings that no longer exist. So picture lock is both an act of discipline — deciding the edit is truly done — and an act of respect for the finishing teams who depend on it. Lock it cleanly, hand it off organized, and your film moves smoothly into its final form.</p>

<h2>Locking and handing off</h2>

<p>What picture lock involves and how to do it right:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Know when it's done.</b> Lock when more cutting stops improving the film and starts just changing it. Test screenings settle, the notes get trivial, the story works — that's the signal to commit.</li>
  <li><b>Lock means locked.</b> Once you lock, the edit doesn't change. Resist "just one more tweak," because every change after lock ripples through color, sound, and VFX. Reopening the cut is a serious decision, not a whim.</li>
  <li><b>Hand off to color.</b> The colorist works from your locked edit to set the film's final look. Deliver organized media and an accurate timeline (an XML/AAF or project) so they can conform to your cut exactly.</li>
  <li><b>Hand off to sound.</b> The sound team takes your locked picture to design, edit, and mix audio properly. Your temp tracks and rough sound become their reference — they build the real thing to the frame.</li>
  <li><b>Hand off to VFX and score.</b> Any visual effects shots and the composer's score are all timed to the locked cut. They need exact durations and reference — which only a true lock can provide.</li>
  <li><b>Deliver clean exports and lists.</b> Give each team what they need: reference video with timecode/burn-ins, an accurate edit list, and organized source media. A clean handoff saves everyone days.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Commit, then let the specialists finish</h2>

<p>The mindset shift of this chapter is learning to <strong>commit</strong> — to accept that at some point the editing has to end so the finishing can begin, and that refusing to lock isn't perfectionism, it's paralysis that holds the whole film hostage. There's genuine courage in picture lock, because you're giving up the endless ability to change things, and there's always a nagging voice saying it could be a little better with one more pass. But the mark of someone who actually finishes films, as opposed to someone who edits forever, is knowing when the film is done — when the cutting has stopped serving the story and started just churning it — and having the discipline to call it and move on. And the reward for committing is enormous, because picture lock is the door to the whole finishing world. This is where your edit connects to the specialized crafts that turn a cut into a finished film: color grading gives it its final look and mood, professional sound design and mixing give it depth and polish, visual effects complete the impossible shots, and a real score replaces your temp music with something made for your film. Each of those is a discipline of its own — with its own artists and its own courses — and each one is built directly onto your locked edit, frame by frame. Your job as the editor is to hand off cleanly: lock the picture for real, keep your project and media organized (exactly the setup discipline from the start of this course paying off again), and give each finishing team accurate lists, reference exports, and source media so they can do their work without fighting your files. Do that, and the transition from edit to finish is smooth, and your film gets the polish it deserves. Refuse to lock, or hand off a mess, and you sabotage all the specialized work waiting downstream. So build the courage to commit, lock the picture when the film is truly done, and hand it off with care — then there's just one thing left, the final step that turns your finished film into something the world can actually watch: exporting and delivery, which is next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Picture lock is an act of courage — you stop cutting and commit. It's also the gate to finishing: color, sound, VFX, and score all build frame-for-frame onto a cut that no longer moves.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The hardest word for me to say on my first film was "locked." I could always find one more thing to nudge, and I nearly held up the whole finish because I wouldn't commit. My post supervisor finally sat me down: every day you don't lock, the colorist, the sound team, and the composer are all waiting, and every tweak after lock costs them a re-do. That reframed it — locking wasn't giving up, it was respecting everyone downstream and trusting my own cut. I locked it. The film got its color, its mix, its score, and it came out better than my endless tweaking ever would have. Know when it's done, and commit.</p>
</div>`,
